WEBVTT

00:00:01.043 --> 00:00:07.023
 All right. Hi, Nathan. So thank you for sitting down with me. Can you give a quick intro of yourself and your internship?

00:00:08.299 --> 00:00:10.379
 Sure. I'm Nathan Odegon.

00:00:10.379 --> 00:00:11.759
 I'm a software engineering student,

00:00:11.759 --> 00:00:13.719
 co-op student at McGill.

00:00:13.719 --> 00:00:15.879
 During summer 25, I interned at

00:00:15.879 --> 00:00:19.299
 Intact Financial Corporation as a test automation developer.

00:00:19.299 --> 00:00:21.519
 It was actually my second co-op.

00:00:21.519 --> 00:00:24.159
 My first one was at Ericsson the year before.

00:00:24.159 --> 00:00:28.679
 So at Intact, I was in a project called Contract UBI,

00:00:28.679 --> 00:00:30.039
 where the team was migrating

00:00:30.039 --> 00:00:32.519
 their usage-based insurance module from

00:00:32.519 --> 00:00:34.719
 an older XML-based system to

00:00:34.719 --> 00:00:37.799
 a newer one built on Java and Spring Boot.

00:00:37.797 --> 00:00:44.837
 So my main job was building a web app called UBI Tools that let QA engineers run automated tests

00:00:44.837 --> 00:00:50.357
 against the insurance services and compare results side by side to spot regressions

00:00:50.357 --> 00:00:56.037
 during the migration. The front end was angular and the backend was Node.js.

00:00:56.511 --> 00:01:08.071
 Alright, perfect. So today I want to focus on defect resolution during development. So can you start by giving me a typical example of how a bug would come up and get dealt with on your team?

00:01:09.809 --> 00:01:12.929
 Sure, yeah.

00:01:12.929 --> 00:01:16.249
 The most common pattern for me was pretty straightforward I'd say.

00:01:16.249 --> 00:01:21.489
 I'd push my code changes to GitHub and the Jenkins pipeline would run automatically.

00:01:21.489 --> 00:01:25.209
 And if any tests broke, the build would fail and I'd get notified right away.

00:01:25.209 --> 00:01:28.829
 So most of the time the issue would be something like a mismatch between what the frontend

00:01:28.829 --> 00:01:34.269
 expected from the backend or a problem with how it was handling the XML data before sending

00:01:34.269 --> 00:01:36.329
 it to the entrance platform.

00:01:36.505 --> 00:01:43.845
 So I would look at the test output, figure out what went wrong and fix it logically, then push again and try again.

00:01:43.845 --> 00:01:51.665
 If the build passed but the behavior still seemed a little bit off, I'd put up a pull request and a teammate would review it.

00:01:51.777 --> 00:01:54.377
 They would sometimes spot things that I've missed,

00:01:54.377 --> 00:01:57.017
 for example, an edge case and the comparison logic,

00:01:57.017 --> 00:02:00.277
 or maybe a situation where the code couldn't handle

00:02:00.277 --> 00:02:02.417
 an empty response properly.

00:02:03.257 --> 00:02:05.977
 I would then address the comments, push the fix,

00:02:05.977 --> 00:02:08.157
 and it would get approved and merged.

00:02:08.157 --> 00:02:10.817
 The whole thing from finding the bug to closing it

00:02:10.817 --> 00:02:12.817
 was usually less than a day.

00:02:12.817 --> 00:02:14.657
 And having the automated pipeline meant

00:02:14.657 --> 00:02:17.857
 that I got feedback very fast, so things didn't pile up.

00:02:18.287 --> 00:02:27.827
 Alright, nice. So now, can you tell me more about the specific case that felt like a real success and how the defect was found and fixed?

00:02:32.327 --> 00:02:40.447
 The one I remember best was when I was connecting UBI tools to Intacct's internal test dashboard called UTA.

00:02:40.883 --> 00:02:44.423
 I wrote an adapter that would take UBI tools test results

00:02:44.423 --> 00:02:48.323
 and format them so that UTA could display them.

00:02:48.323 --> 00:02:51.383
 When I first ran it, everything showed up on the dashboard,

00:02:51.383 --> 00:02:53.823
 but every single test was marked as passed,

00:02:53.823 --> 00:02:56.963
 even the ones that had clearly failed in the UBI tools.

00:02:56.963 --> 00:03:00.603
 So I caught myself while rehearsing for a demo,

00:03:00.593 --> 00:03:04.353
 I was walking through a workflow with some tests that were supposed to fail,

00:03:04.353 --> 00:03:07.393
 and when I switched over to UTA Dashboard, it was all green.

00:03:07.393 --> 00:03:08.993
 Obviously that was wrong.

00:03:08.993 --> 00:03:16.193
 So I went back to the adapter code and traced through how I was translating the result statuses.

00:03:16.185 --> 00:03:19.745
 It turned out that I had a typo in a string comparison.

00:03:19.745 --> 00:03:24.585
 So I was checking for fail instead of failed.

00:03:24.585 --> 00:03:26.865
 So the condition never matched and everything

00:03:26.865 --> 00:03:29.325
 defaulted to pass.

00:03:29.325 --> 00:03:31.905
 It was a small, kind of embarrassing mistake.

00:03:31.913 --> 00:03:35.213
 But the important thing was that I caught it before the actual demo,

00:03:35.213 --> 00:03:36.953
 otherwise it would have been embarrassing.

00:03:36.953 --> 00:03:40.253
 I fixed it, ran it again with a mix of passing and failing tests

00:03:40.253 --> 00:03:43.053
 to make sure the dashboard showed up the right statuses.

00:03:43.053 --> 00:03:46.673
 And then I added a unit test for that mapping logic

00:03:46.673 --> 00:03:48.513
 so that the same kind of thing couldn't happen

00:03:48.513 --> 00:03:50.733
 and I couldn't slip through again.

00:03:50.733 --> 00:03:54.933
 The whole process from catching the bug to having it fixed and tested

00:03:54.933 --> 00:03:57.473
 took about less than two hours, I'd say.

00:03:58.238 --> 00:04:09.218
 Okay, nice. So that was a real success on your part. But on the other side, can you describe a case that was more of a failure, where a defect wasn't caught the way you would have wanted?

00:04:13.240 --> 00:04:16.320
 Yeah, okay, so this one kind of stuck with me.

00:04:16.320 --> 00:04:20.320
 The core feature of UBI tools was the comparison view, right?

00:04:20.320 --> 00:04:23.420
 You pick two test runs and the tool shows you exactly

00:04:23.420 --> 00:04:25.840
 what changed between the responses.

00:04:25.840 --> 00:04:29.300
 It worked by parsing the XML responses field by field

00:04:29.300 --> 00:04:31.040
 and flagging differences.

00:04:31.040 --> 00:04:33.520
 I had it working well for most of the endpoints

00:04:33.520 --> 00:04:35.860
 I was testing, but late in the internship,

00:04:35.860 --> 00:04:38.260
 a developer on the team told me that the comparison

00:04:38.260 --> 00:04:40.060
 was showing false positives

00:04:40.060 --> 00:04:42.760
 for one of the discount calculation endpoints.

00:04:43.379 --> 00:04:46.959
 it was flagging fields as different

00:04:46.959 --> 00:04:49.199
 even when the actual values hadn't changed.

00:04:49.199 --> 00:04:50.159
 So that was weird.

00:04:50.159 --> 00:04:50.999
 When I looked into it,

00:04:50.999 --> 00:04:53.859
 the problem was floating point precision.

00:04:53.859 --> 00:04:56.819
 So the discount endpoint returned decimal numbers

00:04:56.819 --> 00:04:58.279
 in its responses.

00:04:58.279 --> 00:05:01.159
 And JavaScript sometimes stores a value,

00:05:01.159 --> 00:05:05.319
 for example, take 0.10, 0.10,

00:05:05.319 --> 00:05:10.319
 as 0.1 with 13 zeros and a one internally.

00:05:10.359 --> 00:05:12.519
 So there's a mismatch there.

00:05:12.522 --> 00:05:19.622
 So when the tool compared that 0.10 against another response,

00:05:19.622 --> 00:05:23.282
 it flagged them as different even though they were effectively the same value.

00:05:23.762 --> 00:05:28.162
 The frustrating part in that is that floating point precision is something I already knew about,

00:05:28.162 --> 00:05:32.202
 I learned about that, and every developer runs into it at some point.

00:05:32.202 --> 00:05:35.762
 So I just never thought to account for it in the comparison logic

00:05:36.162 --> 00:05:40.062
 because of all the testing I've been doing was using whole numbers.

00:05:41.344 --> 00:05:44.264
 So the bug had been sitting in the code for weeks

00:05:44.264 --> 00:05:46.944
 before anyone actually noticed that,

00:05:49.704 --> 00:05:52.504
 before it happened to anyone when testing the endpoint.

00:05:52.504 --> 00:05:53.604
 And the fix was simple.

00:05:53.604 --> 00:05:56.364
 I added a rounding step for numeric fields

00:05:56.364 --> 00:05:57.864
 before comparing them.

00:05:57.865 --> 00:06:05.305
 But during those weeks, QA engineers had been using the tool and might have just been trusting results that were slightly wrong, I guess.

00:06:05.305 --> 00:06:12.425
 I should have tested with a wider variety of data types from the start, not just the ones I happened to be working with.

00:06:12.425 --> 00:06:17.625
 So yeah, I guess you learned from that simple mistake.

00:06:17.625 --> 00:06:22.665
 But was this defect reported through JIRA or did it come up informally?

00:06:24.375 --> 00:06:27.075
 Yeah, so it actually came up informally.

00:06:27.075 --> 00:06:29.715
 The developer mentioned it during a stand-up meeting.

00:06:30.012 --> 00:06:33.412
 But we actually had a Jira workflow in place,

00:06:33.412 --> 00:06:38.052
 so I created a bug ticket that same day with a description,

00:06:38.052 --> 00:06:42.372
 with the steps to reproduce it, which endpoints it affected, blah blah blah.

00:06:42.372 --> 00:06:47.372
 My supervisor, Javier, saw it in the backlog and pulled it into the current sprint.

00:06:47.372 --> 00:06:50.372
 Having that ticket meant the fix was tracked properly,

00:06:50.372 --> 00:06:54.772
 and anyone looking at the code later could trace the commit back to the Jira ticket,

00:06:54.772 --> 00:06:57.812
 and then understand why the rounding logic was there.

00:06:58.429 --> 00:07:02.109
 I've come to think that kind of traceability is very important

00:07:02.109 --> 00:07:06.189
 since you want the next person who reads the code

00:07:06.189 --> 00:07:09.269
 to be able to understand why a decision was made

00:07:09.269 --> 00:07:11.149
 and not just what was changed.

00:07:12.029 --> 00:07:13.449
 Okay, nice.

00:07:13.449 --> 00:07:15.449
 So let's end off with this.

00:07:15.449 --> 00:07:18.869
 So if you could change one thing about how defects

00:07:18.869 --> 00:07:21.569
 were handled during your internship, what would it be?

00:07:23.289 --> 00:07:25.389
 That's a good question.

00:07:27.690 --> 00:07:33.090
 I think I push for broader test coverage across different types of data early on.

00:07:33.650 --> 00:07:37.210
 And I make that part of the checklist for finishing a feature.

00:07:37.495 --> 00:07:43.535
 rather than something that only happens when someone stumbles across a problem.

00:07:43.535 --> 00:07:51.735
 The floating point bug that I faced only got caught because one specific developer happened to test one specific endpoint.

00:07:51.735 --> 00:07:58.155
 So if nobody had used that endpoint during my internship, the bug would have shift with the tool.

00:07:58.285 --> 00:08:05.045
 So a more deliberate approach, for example, sitting down and asking what kinds of data does this feature actually need to handle,

00:08:05.585 --> 00:08:11.865
 and then writing tests for each kind of data before calling it done, would have caught that much earlier.

00:08:12.065 --> 00:08:12.985
 It would have been a better option.

00:08:13.705 --> 00:08:15.925
 All right. So thank you, Nathan, for today.

00:08:16.565 --> 00:08:20.705
 Thank you for attending this interview and hope you have a nice day.

00:08:21.785 --> 00:08:23.405
 No worries. My pleasure. Have a nice day.

